Categories of passengers most likely to survive the Titanic disaster.¶

It would appear that the policy of women and children first did in fact apply. The highest probability for survival went to a woman travelling first class. Females of all passenger classes faired better than someone travelling first class when gender is not considered. A woman travelling third class had a higher survival rate than a man travelling first class.

Beyond gender, passenger class was the greatest predictive variable. A male travelling first class had a higher survival rate than a male travelling either second or third class. First class passengers had a higher survival rate than second class passengers, who had a higher survival rate than third class passengers.

Historic Survival Rate Table

The following algorithms were utilized during the course of this analysis;

  • Decision Tree
  • Gaussian
  • Gradient Boosting
  • K Neighbors
  • Logistic Regression
  • Multi Layer Perceptron
  • Random Forest
  • Stochastic Gradient Descent
  • Support Vector

In addition to examining passengers as a whole, passengers were also divided into groupings by gender and passenger class.

For males, familial considerations in terms of who they were travelling with on the ship did not have an effect on survivability. Additional detail is provided below.

Hypothetical Survivability by Age

As expected, in accordance with the policy of women and children first, survivability was higher at younger ages. However, no abrupt drop-off in survivability was observed at a certain age. This would suggest that the crew putting passengers on to life boats were not applying any specific cut-off age at which a passenger was no longer considered a child. The drop in survivability by age was gradual and uniform across most models. A slight advantage can be seen with children under ten years of age. Possibilty because these children could occupy the same seat as the mother.

Hypothetical Survivability

As expected, models predicting from hypothetical passenger features show that; females had a higher survivability probability than males, and that survivability decreased by passenger class.

When considering familial relationships, passengers travelling by themselves showed a higher survivability rate on some models. This may be accounted for in instances where there was only one seat left available in a life boat. This advantage probably accured primarily to females.

In terms of familial relationships, passengers travelling with a spouse or a sibling but not a child had the highest survivability. This advantage probably accrued primarily to females. Possibly indicating that married couples were willing to separate for the sake of survivability. This would also give the female spouse an advantage in situations where there was only a single available seat on a life boat.

Passengers consisting of a single parent and a child had the second highest survivability, possibly because the single parent may be male.

The last familial configuration consisting of a married couple with a child faired worst in terms of survivability. Possibly indicating the husbands were more willing to separate from wives than from wives and children. This may also suggest that families chose to risk death as opposed to being separated. Possibly a sign of human optimism in the hopes that another boat would become available that could accommodate all members.

Detailed explanation of the logic of the analysis¶

Children younger than one year old will be considered to be one year old, since it is assumed that the difference in age would not affect survivability. Missing ages were assigned by the average of gender and passenger class.

The primary survival differentiators were determined to be; gender, passenger class, and familial relationships. Subgroupings were created in accordance with these differentiators. Passenger data for all passengers was examined as well. Historical survivability was then calculated for each group by simply dividing survived by the group total.

These groups then formed the basis for the machine learning algorithms described previously. These models were then used to examine familial relationship and age predictors on survivability. This was accomplished by creating a hypothetical group of passengers where each unique combination of; gender, passenger class, familial relationship was created for each age present on the ship. Survivability was then predicted using all models against this data set.

Other attributes used for the analysis.¶

  • Pclass, used in derived form, broken out into three columns for each possible categorical value.
  • Sex, used in a derived form, broken out into two columns for each possible categorical value.
  • SibSp, used in derived form, as described below.
  • Parch, used in derived form, as described below.

Complete list of all attributes used.¶

  • Survived.
  • Pclass, used in derived form, broken out into three columns for each possible categorical value.
  • Sex, used in a derived form, broken out into two columns for each possible categorical value.
  • Age.
  • SibSp, used in derived form, as described below.
  • Parch, used in derived form, as described below.

Engineered attributes¶

In order to examine whether the decision to remain on board was in some way affected by whether the passenger was travelling alone or with others, three new columns were added based on the existing 'SibSp' and 'Parch' columns. Columns 'WithSiblingSpouse', 'WithParent', and 'WithFamily' were added. True values derived as follows;

  • WithSiblingSpouse true if SibSp is greater than zero
  • WithParent true if Parch greater than zero
  • WithFamily true if SibSp greater than zero and Parch greater than zero.

The addition of these columns produced mixed results. The highest predictive accuracies when examining all passengers were obtained from algorithms when including familial features. This would suggest that familial considerations were taken into account.

Excluded attributes¶

  • PassengerId considered irrelevant.

  • Passenger number considered irrelevant.
  • Cabin number considered irrelevant.
  • Fare considered irrelevant.

    def preprocess_data(self):
        
        for passenger_key, passenger_data in self.file_data.iterrows():
            
            if passenger_data['Age'] < 1:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'Age'] = 1
            
            if passenger_data['SibSp'] != 0:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'WithSiblingSpouse'] = 1
            else:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'WithSiblingSpouse'] = 0
                
            if passenger_data['Parch'] != 0:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'WithParent'] = 1
            else:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'WithParent'] = 0
                
            if passenger_data['SibSp'] != 0 and passenger_data['Parch'] != 0:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'WithFamily'] = 1
            else:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'WithFamily'] = 0    
            
            if passenger_data['Sex'] == 'female':
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'Male'] = 0
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'Female'] = 1
            elif passenger_data['Sex'] == 'male':
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'Male'] = 1
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'Female'] = 0
                
            if passenger_data['Pclass'] == 1:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'FirstClass'] = 1
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'SecondClass'] = 0
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'ThirdClass'] = 0
            elif passenger_data['Pclass'] == 2:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'FirstClass'] = 0
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'SecondClass'] = 1
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'ThirdClass'] = 0
            elif passenger_data['Pclass'] == 3:
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'FirstClass'] = 0
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'SecondClass'] = 0
                self.file_data.loc[passenger_key, 'ThirdClass'] = 1    
                
        self.all_passengers = self.file_data.copy()

    def average_age(self):
        
        self.average_age_list.append(['Female Third Class', round(self.female_third_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Female Second Class', round(self.female_second_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Female First Class', round(self.female_first_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Male Third Class', round(self.male_third_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Male Second_class', round(self.male_second_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Male First_class', round(self.male_first_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Female', round(self.female_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Male', round(self.male_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Third Class', round(self.third_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['Second Class', round(self.second_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['First Class', round(self.first_class_ages.mean())])
        self.average_age_list.append(['All Passengers', round(self.all_passengers_ages.mean())])

        self.average_age_df = pd.DataFrame(self.average_age_list, columns = ['Passenger Type', 'Average Age'])

        sns.barplot(data = self.average_age_df, x = 'Average Age', y = 'Passenger Type')

    def survival_summary(self):

        (self.male_second_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].sum() / self.male_second_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].count())])
        
        self.survival_summary_list.append(['Male Third Class', \
        (self.male_third_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].sum() / self.male_third_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].count())])
        
        self.survival_summary_list.append(['First Class', \
        (self.first_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].sum() / self.first_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].count())])
        
        self.survival_summary_list.append(['Second Class', \
        (self.second_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].sum() / self.second_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].count())])
        
        self.survival_summary_list.append(['Third Class', \
        (self.third_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].sum() / self.third_class.loc[:, 'Survived'].count())])
        
        self.survival_summary_list.append(['All Passengers', \
        (self.all_passengers.loc[:, 'Survived'].sum() / self.all_passengers.loc[:, 'Survived'].count())])
        
        self.survival_summary_df = pd.DataFrame(self.survival_summary_list, columns = ['Passenger Type', 'Survival Probability'])

        sns.barplot(data = self.survival_summary_df, x = 'Survival Probability', y = 'Passenger Type')
    
    def run_algorithm(self, \
                      algorithm, \
                      predictive_features_train, \
                      predictive_features_test, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      include_familial, \
                      include_gender, \
                      algorithm_description):

        classifier = algorithm
        classifier.fit(predictive_features_train, targets_train)
        prediction = classifier.predict(predictive_features_test)

        print(classification_report(targets_test, prediction))
        
        self.hypothetical_passengers(passenger_ages, include_familial, include_gender, classifier, algorithm_description)

    def non_familial_models(self, population_subset, passenger_ages, include_gender):

        targets = population_subset.loc[:, 'Survived']
        predictive_features = population_subset.loc[:,\
        ['Age', 'Male', 'Female', 'FirstClass', 'SecondClass', 'ThirdClass']]

        predictive_features_train, \
        predictive_features_test, \
        targets_train, \
        targets_test = train_test_split(predictive_features, \
                                        targets, test_size = 0.2, \
                                        random_state = 42)

        targets_train = np.ravel(targets_train)

        scaler = StandardScaler()

        scaler.fit(predictive_features_train)
        predictive_features_train_scaled = scaler.transform(predictive_features_train)
        predictive_features_test_scaled = scaler.transform(predictive_features_test)

        print('Gradient Boosting')

        self.run_algorithm(GradientBoostingClassifier(), \
                      predictive_features_train_scaled, \
                      predictive_features_test_scaled, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      False, \
                      include_gender, \
                      'Gradient Boosting')

        print('Decision Tree')

        self.run_algorithm(DecisionTreeClassifier(), \
                      predictive_features_train_scaled, \
                      predictive_features_test_scaled, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      False, \
                      include_gender, \
                      'Decision Tree')

        print('Stochastic Gradient Descent')

        self.run_algorithm(SGDClassifier(), \
                      predictive_features_train_scaled, \
                      predictive_features_test_scaled, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      False, \
                      include_gender, \
                      'Stochastic Gradient Descent')
        
        print('Gaussian')

        self.run_algorithm(GaussianNB(), \
                      predictive_features_train_scaled, \
                      predictive_features_test_scaled, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      False, \
                      include_gender, \
                      'Gaussian')

        print('Logistic Regression')

        self.run_algorithm(LogisticRegression(), \
                      predictive_features_train_scaled, \
                      predictive_features_test_scaled, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      False, \
                      include_gender, \
                      'Logistic Regression')

        print('K Neighbors')

        self.run_algorithm(KNeighborsClassifier(), \
                      predictive_features_train_scaled, \
                      predictive_features_test_scaled, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      False, \
                      include_gender, \
                      'K Neighbors')

        print('Random Forest')

        self.run_algorithm(RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = 200), \
                      predictive_features_train_scaled, \
                      predictive_features_test_scaled, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      False, \
                      include_gender, \
                      'Random Forest')

        print('Support Vector')

        self.run_algorithm(svm.SVC(), \
                      predictive_features_train_scaled, \
                      predictive_features_test_scaled, \
                      targets_train, \
                      targets_test, \
                      passenger_ages, \
                      False, \
                      include_gender, \
                      'Support Vector')

        print('Multi Layer Perceptron')

        classifier = MLPClassifier(hidden_layer_sizes = (6,6,6), max_iter = 500)
        classifier.fit(predictive_features_train_scaled, targets_train)
        prediction = classifier.predict(predictive_features_test_scaled)

        print(classification_report(targets_test, prediction))
        
        self.hypothetical_passengers(passenger_ages, False, include_gender, classifier, 'Multi Layer Perceptron')

    def hypothetical_passengers(self, passenger_ages, include_familial, include_gender, classifier, algorithm_description):

        ages = []

        for age in passenger_ages:
            age = round(age)    
            ages.append(age)

        ages = set(ages)

        hypothetical_features = []

        for age in ages:

            if include_familial:
                
                if include_gender == 'M' or include_gender == 'A':
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,0,1,0,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,1,1,0,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,0,1,0,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,0,1,0,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,0,1,0,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,1,1,0,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,0,1,0,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,0,1,0,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,0,1,0,1,0,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,1,1,0,1,0,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,0,1,0,1,0,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,0,1,0,1,0,0])
                
                if include_gender == 'F' or include_gender == 'A':
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,0,0,1,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,1,0,1,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,0,0,1,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,0,0,1,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,0,0,1,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,1,0,1,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,0,0,1,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,0,0,1,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,0,0,1,1,0,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,0,1,0,1,1,0,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,0,0,1,1,0,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,0,0,1,1,0,0])
            else:
                
                if include_gender == 'M' or include_gender == 'A':
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,1,0,1,0,0])
                
                if include_gender == 'F' or include_gender == 'A':
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,0,0,1])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,0,1,0])
                    hypothetical_features.append([age,0,1,1,0,0])
                
        scaler = StandardScaler()

        scaler.fit(hypothetical_features)
        hypothetical_features_scaled = scaler.transform(hypothetical_features)
        
        prediction = classifier.predict(hypothetical_features_scaled)
        
        hypothetical_features = np.column_stack((prediction, hypothetical_features))
        
        familial_relationships = []
        
        if include_familial:
            
            WithSpouseSibling = 0
            WithParent = 0
            WithBoth = 0
            WithNeither = 0
            
            for prediction in hypothetical_features:
                
                if prediction[2] == 1:
                    WithSpouseSibling = WithSpouseSibling + prediction[0]
                elif prediction[3] == 1:
                    WithParent = WithParent + prediction[0]
                elif prediction[4] == 1:
                    WithBoth = WithBoth + prediction[0]    
                else:
                    WithNeither = WithNeither + prediction[0]
                    
            familial_relationships.append(['Travelling with Spouse Sibling', WithSpouseSibling])
            familial_relationships.append(['Travelling with Parent', WithParent])
            familial_relationships.append(['Travelling with Spouse Sibling Parent', WithBoth])
            familial_relationships.append(['Travelling Alone', WithNeither])
            
            familial_relationships_df = pd.DataFrame(familial_relationships, columns = ['Relationship Type', 'Survived'])
            
            print(familial_relationships_df)
            print(' ')
            
        age_count = {}

        for age in ages:
            age_count[age] = 0

        for age_key, age_survived in age_count.items():

            for prediction in hypothetical_features:

                if prediction[0] != 1: continue

                if age_key == prediction[1]:
                    age_count[age_key] = age_count[age_key] + prediction[0]

        self.age_count_summary.append(age_count)
        
        predictions_list = []
        
        for prediction_row in hypothetical_features:
            
            prediction_list = []
            
            if include_familial:
                prediction_list.append(algorithm_description)
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[0])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[1])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[2])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[3])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[4])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[5])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[6])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[7])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[8])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[9])
            else:
                prediction_list.append(algorithm_description)
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[0])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[1])
                prediction_list.append(0)
                prediction_list.append(0)
                prediction_list.append(0)
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[2])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[3])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[4])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[5])
                prediction_list.append(prediction_row[6])
                
            predictions_list.append(prediction_list)
        
        predictions_df = pd.DataFrame(predictions_list, \
                                      columns=['Algorithm_Description', \
                                               'Survived', \
                                               'Age', \
                                               'WithSiblingSpouse', \
                                               'WithParent', \
                                               'WithFamily', \
                                               'Male', \
                                               'Female', \
                                               'FirstClass', \
                                               'SecondClass', \
                                               'ThirdClass'])
        
        self.hypothetical_predictions = pd.concat([self.hypothetical_predictions, predictions_df], axis = 0)

    def prediction_graphs(self, algorithm_description, include_familial):
        
        algorithm_df = self.hypothetical_predictions[(self.hypothetical_predictions['Algorithm_Description'] == algorithm_description)].copy()
    
        gender_survival = []
        
        gender_survival.append(['Female', \
        (algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['Female'] == 1), \
                          'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['Female'] == 1), 'Survived'].count())])
        
        gender_survival.append(['Male', \
        (algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['Male'] == 1), \
                          'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['Male'] == 1), 'Survived'].count())])

        gender_survival_df = pd.DataFrame(gender_survival, columns = ['Gender', 'Survived'])

        sns.barplot(data = gender_survival_df, x = 'Survived', y = 'Gender').set_title(algorithm_description)
        plt.show()
        
        class_survival = []
        
        class_survival.append(['First Class', \
        (algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['FirstClass'] == 1), \
                          'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['FirstClass'] == 1), 'Survived'].count())])
        
        class_survival.append(['Second Class', \
        (algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['SecondClass'] == 1), \
                          'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['SecondClass'] == 1), 'Survived'].count())])

        class_survival.append(['Third Class', \
        (algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['ThirdClass'] == 1), \
                          'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['ThirdClass'] == 1), 'Survived'].count())])
        
        class_survival_df = pd.DataFrame(class_survival, columns = ['Passenger Class', 'Survived'])

        sns.barplot(data = class_survival_df, x = 'Survived', y = 'Passenger Class').set_title(algorithm_description)
        plt.show()
        
        if include_familial:
            
            familial_survival = []
        
            familial_survival.append(['Sibling or Spouse', \
            (algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['WithSiblingSpouse'] == 1), \
                              'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['WithSiblingSpouse'] == 1), 'Survived'].count())])

            familial_survival.append(['Parent', \
            (algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['WithParent'] == 1), \
                              'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['WithParent'] == 1), 'Survived'].count())])

            familial_survival.append(['Family', \
            (algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['WithFamily'] == 1), \
                              'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[(algorithm_df['WithFamily'] == 1), 'Survived'].count())])

            familial_survival.append(['Travelling Alone', \
            (algorithm_df.loc[((algorithm_df['WithFamily'] == 0) & \
                               (algorithm_df['WithParent'] == 0) & \
                               (algorithm_df['WithSiblingSpouse'] == 0)), \
                              'Survived'].sum() / algorithm_df.loc[ \
                               ((algorithm_df['WithFamily'] == 0) & \
                                (algorithm_df['WithParent'] == 0) & \
                                (algorithm_df['WithSiblingSpouse'] == 0)), \
                              'Survived'].count())])
            
            familial_survival_df = pd.DataFrame(familial_survival, columns = ['Passenger Relationship', 'Survived'])

            sns.barplot(data = familial_survival_df, x = 'Survived', y = 'Passenger Relationship').set_title(algorithm_description)
            plt.show()

Historic Survival Rate¶

It would appear that the policy of women and children first did in fact apply. The highest probability for survival went to a woman travelling first class. Females of all passenger classes faired better than someone travelling first class when gender is not considered. A woman travelling third class had a higher survival rate than a man travelling first class.

Beyond gender, passenger class was the greatest predictive variable. A male travelling first class had a higher survival rate than a male travelling either second or third class. First class passengers had a higher survival rate than second class passengers, who had a higher survival rate than third class passengers.

Hypothetical Survivability by Age¶

As expected, in accordance with the policy of women and children first, survivability was higher at younger ages. However, no abrupt drop-off in survivability was observed at a certain age. This would suggest that the crew putting passengers on to life boats were not applying any specific cut-off age at which a passenger was no longer considered a child. The drop in survivability by age was gradual and uniform across most models. A slight advantage can be seen with children under ten years of age. Possibilty because these children could occupy the same seat as the mother.

        elif age >= 41 and age <= 50:

        elif age >= 51 and age <= 60:
            age51_60 = age51_60 + occurrence
        elif age >= 61 and age <= 70:
            age61_70 = age61_70 + occurrence
        elif age >= 71 and age <= 80:
            age71_80 = age71_80 + occurrence
        
        ages.append(age)        
        occurrences.append(int(occurrence))

Hypothetical Survivability¶

As expected, models predicting from hypothetical passenger features show that; females had a higher survivability probability than males, and that survivability decreased by passenger class.

When considering familial relationships, passengers travelling by themselves showed a higher survivability rate on some models. This may be accounted for in instances where there was only one seat left available in a life boat. This advantage probably accured primarily to females.

In terms of familial relationships, passengers travelling with a spouse or a sibling but not a child had the highest survivability. This advantage probably accrued primarily to females. Possibly indicating that married couples were willing to separate for the sake of survivability. This would also give the female spouse an advantage in situations where there was only a single available seat on a life boat.

Passengers consisting of a single parent and a child had the second highest survivability, possibly because the single parent may be male.

The last familial configuration consisting of a married couple with a child faired worst in terms of survivability. Possibly indicating the husbands were more willing to separate from wives than from wives and children. This may also suggest that families chose to risk death as opposed to being separated. Possibly a sign of human optimism in the hopes that another boat would become available that could accommodate all members.
